a computer geologist

00:01:05.232 --> 00:01:07.534 align:middle line:84%
and also the first
technical operations

00:01:07.534 --> 00:01:09.036 align:middle line:90%
manager at Cisco Systems.

00:01:09.036 --> 00:01:12.506 align:middle line:84%
And he's here to help us
understand this critical time

00:01:12.506 --> 00:01:13.307 align:middle line:90%
in history.

00:01:13.307 --> 00:01:16.777 align:middle line:84%
He's the author of the book
called Deep Truth: Igniting

00:01:16.777 --> 00:01:20.614 align:middle line:84%
the Memory of Our Origin,
History, Destiny, and Fate.

00:01:20.614 --> 00:01:21.682 align:middle line:90%
Hello and welcome.

00:01:21.682 --> 00:01:21.949 align:middle line:90%
>>GREGG BRADEN: Hello, Lisa.

00:01:21.949 --> 00:01:22.683 align:middle line:90%
It's so good to be here.

00:01:22.683 --> 00:01:24.351 align:middle line:84%
And I am so happy to
be with all of you,

00:01:24.351 --> 00:01:26.687 align:middle line:84%
our viewers all over
the world tonight.

00:01:26.687 --> 00:01:27.187 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:01:27.187 --> 00:01:28.755 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Thank you for
the opportunity to share.

00:01:28.755 --> 00:01:30.257 align:middle line:90%
There's so much to talk about.

00:01:30.257 --> 00:01:31.358 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: There's a lot, yes.

00:01:31.358 --> 00:01:32.359 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: My sense
is our time together

00:01:32.359 --> 00:01:33.560 align:middle line:90%
is going to go by very quickly.

00:01:33.560 --> 00:01:34.328 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, it's
going to be great.

00:01:34.328 --> 00:01:36.896 align:middle line:84%
This is going to be an
amazing amount of information

00:01:36.896 --> 00:01:39.199 align:middle line:84%
and education for you
so stay with us here.

00:01:39.199 --> 00:01:41.401 align:middle line:84%
So tell me a little bit
about the book Deep Truth.

00:01:41.401 --> 00:01:42.636 align:middle line:90%
Now what does the title mean?

00:01:42.636 --> 00:01:44.003 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well,
the book itself--

00:01:44.003 --> 00:01:47.941 align:middle line:84%
I wrote this book in response
to our time in history.

00:01:47.941 --> 00:01:50.610 align:middle line:10%
I think if you're watching
this, it's no secret to you

00:01:50.610 --> 00:01:53.479 align:middle line:10%
that this is no ordinary time
in the history of our country,

00:01:53.479 --> 00:01:54.948 align:middle line:10%
in the history of
our civilization,

00:01:54.948 --> 00:01:56.750 align:middle line:10%
in the history of our world.

00:01:56.750 --> 00:01:57.818 align:middle line:10%
It's not our imagination.

00:01:57.818 --> 00:01:59.519 align:middle line:10%
The best minds of our
time are telling us

00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:02.089 align:middle line:10%
that we are facing the greatest
number, Lisa, the greatest

00:02:02.089 --> 00:02:04.391 align:middle line:10%
number and the
greatest magnitude

00:02:04.391 --> 00:02:07.794 align:middle line:10%
of crises ever to face
a single generation all

00:02:07.794 --> 00:02:11.031 align:middle line:10%
funneled into this little window
of time at the end of the 20th

00:02:11.031 --> 00:02:12.799 align:middle line:10%
and now the 21st century.

00:02:12.799 --> 00:02:15.135 align:middle line:84%
The book, Deep
Truth, the title--

00:02:15.135 --> 00:02:17.004 align:middle line:84%
where this title comes
from, it's actually

00:02:17.004 --> 00:02:21.041 align:middle line:84%
a quote from one of the great
physicists of the 20th century,

00:02:21.041 --> 00:02:21.808 align:middle line:90%
Niels Bohr.

00:02:21.808 --> 00:02:24.044 align:middle line:84%
He was having a conversation
with Albert Einstein.

00:02:24.044 --> 00:02:25.478 align:middle line:90%
They were talking about truth--

00:02:25.478 --> 00:02:27.848 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I sure would have
loved to be a fly on that wall.

00:02:27.848 --> 00:02:28.882 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Oh, absolutely.

00:02:28.882 --> 00:02:31.385 align:middle line:84%
And in this case, it was the
nature of scientific truth.

00:02:31.385 --> 00:02:33.553 align:middle line:84%
And what Niels
Bohr said is this,

00:02:33.553 --> 00:02:37.724 align:middle line:84%
he said it is the hallmark of
any deep truth-- in this case,

00:02:37.724 --> 00:02:42.696 align:middle line:84%
a scientific truth-- that its
negation is also a deep truth.

00:02:42.696 --> 00:02:46.833 align:middle line:84%
Now, what that means is that
the scientific foundation

00:02:46.833 --> 00:02:48.769 align:middle line:84%
upon which we base
many of our beliefs

00:02:48.769 --> 00:02:51.505 align:middle line:84%
about who we are, our
relationship to ourselves,

00:02:51.505 --> 00:02:54.141 align:middle line:84%
to our bodies, to one another,
and to the world-- it's

00:02:54.141 --> 00:02:57.644 align:middle line:84%
based upon a foundation
of scientific beliefs--

00:02:57.644 --> 00:03:01.848 align:middle line:84%
new discoveries are now
overturning those beliefs.

00:03:01.848 --> 00:03:02.716 align:middle line:90%
That's the good news.

00:03:02.716 --> 00:03:04.384 align:middle line:84%
The flip side of
this is there is

00:03:04.384 --> 00:03:08.288 align:middle line:84%
a reluctance and, in some
cases, an outright resistance

00:03:08.288 --> 00:03:11.858 align:middle line:84%
for the mainstream media,
mainstream academia,

00:03:11.858 --> 00:03:15.462 align:middle line:84%
classrooms, textbooks to
share the new discoveries.

00:03:15.462 --> 00:03:16.963 align:middle line:84%
This would be
important at any time.

00:03:16.963 --> 00:03:18.532 align:middle line:84%
But it's especially
critical right now

00:03:18.532 --> 00:03:21.635 align:middle line:84%
because we are at this moment of
crisis in our time in history.

00:03:21.635 --> 00:03:23.770 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Absolutely, and
it's to no fault of theirs.

00:03:23.770 --> 00:03:25.872 align:middle line:84%
Because these are
such new discoveries.

00:03:25.872 --> 00:03:28.341 align:middle line:84%
And the whole idea of
doing a show like this

00:03:28.341 --> 00:03:31.545 align:middle line:84%
is to get it into
the minds of people.

00:03:31.545 --> 00:03:33.346 align:middle line:84%
Because this is going
to shatter beliefs.

00:03:33.346 --> 00:03:36.083 align:middle line:84%
This is going to shatter
systems that we were taught

00:03:36.083 --> 00:03:38.852 align:middle line:84%
in school about
history and evolution.

00:03:38.852 --> 00:03:39.986 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Absolutely, Lisa.

00:03:39.986 --> 00:03:42.555 align:middle line:84%
And I want to be very
clear that this is not

00:03:42.555 --> 00:03:43.656 align:middle line:90%
the teacher's fault.

00:03:43.656 --> 00:03:45.826 align:middle line:84%
There's a story, there's
a scientific story

00:03:45.826 --> 00:03:47.627 align:middle line:84%
that has developed
and been embraced

00:03:47.627 --> 00:03:49.496 align:middle line:84%
for over a century
and a half about who

00:03:49.496 --> 00:03:51.465 align:middle line:84%
we are and our
relationship to the world.

00:03:51.465 --> 00:03:54.101 align:middle line:84%
And it takes time to
change that story.

00:03:54.101 --> 00:03:54.868 align:middle line:90%
We know that.

00:03:54.868 --> 00:03:56.269 align:middle line:84%
What the experts
are telling us is

00:03:56.269 --> 00:03:59.072 align:middle line:84%
we don't have decades
to change the way

00:03:59.072 --> 00:04:00.574 align:middle line:84%
we think of ourselves
so that we can

00:04:00.574 --> 00:04:01.942 align:middle line:90%
solve the crises of our time.

00:04:01.942 --> 00:04:05.112 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I think this
program is so important today.

00:04:05.112 --> 00:04:07.447 align:middle line:84%
So what I've done
for our viewers,

00:04:07.447 --> 00:04:08.949 align:middle line:84%
I've put together
a few images that

00:04:08.949 --> 00:04:11.451 align:middle line:84%
will kind of highlight
this conversation

00:04:11.451 --> 00:04:13.520 align:middle line:84%
and share some of
the discoveries

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:16.490 align:middle line:84%
and some of the rare images
from ancient civilizations

00:04:16.490 --> 00:04:18.524 align:middle line:84%
and things as we go
through our conversation.

00:04:18.524 --> 00:04:19.159 align:middle line:90%
Are you OK--

00:04:19.159 --> 00:04:19.959 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:21.361 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: --if we use these to--

00:04:21.361 --> 00:04:22.229 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:04:22.229 --> 00:04:23.263 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --take us
through where we are.

00:04:23.263 --> 00:04:25.098 align:middle line:84%
If you're looking at
your screen right now--

00:04:25.098 --> 00:04:27.534 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This is, by the way,
a very, very special treat.

00:04:27.534 --> 00:04:29.636 align:middle line:84%
Because a lot of these
images-- Gregg owns them.

00:04:29.636 --> 00:04:31.805 align:middle line:84%
And we're seeing them
for the first time here.

00:04:31.805 --> 00:04:32.439 align:middle line:90%
So this is--

00:04:32.439 --> 00:04:33.140 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Some of them.

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:33.807 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --good stuff.

00:04:33.807 --> 00:04:35.008 align:middle line:10%
>>BRADEN: So then, if you're
looking at your screen

00:04:35.008 --> 00:04:36.443 align:middle line:10%
right now, what
you're seeing, this

00:04:36.443 --> 00:04:38.778 align:middle line:10%
is a special edition of
"Scientific American."

00:04:38.778 --> 00:04:41.615 align:middle line:10%
It was released in
September of 2005.

00:04:41.615 --> 00:04:44.183 align:middle line:10%
And if you think back, we were
living a very different world

00:04:44.183 --> 00:04:46.253 align:middle line:10%
from 2005 and where
we are right now.

00:04:46.253 --> 00:04:47.354 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Not so long ago.

00:04:47.354 --> 00:04:50.857 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: But this was some of
the leading minds of our time.

00:04:50.857 --> 00:04:53.727 align:middle line:84%
Scientists, engineers, social
architects, political leaders,

00:04:53.727 --> 00:04:56.129 align:middle line:84%
spiritual leaders, religious
leaders, philosophers,

00:04:56.129 --> 00:04:57.230 align:middle line:90%
they all came together.

00:04:57.230 --> 00:05:01.067 align:middle line:84%
And they were asked, what makes
our time in history so unique?

00:05:01.067 --> 00:05:03.803 align:middle line:84%
What's different now about
any other time in history?

00:05:03.803 --> 00:05:05.906 align:middle line:84%
And the answers,
Lisa, were so profound

00:05:05.906 --> 00:05:08.508 align:middle line:84%
that "Scientific American"
released a special edition

00:05:08.508 --> 00:05:10.410 align:middle line:84%
to bring the rest
of the world up

00:05:10.410 --> 00:05:13.079 align:middle line:84%
to speed with what the experts
were telling us was happening.

00:05:13.079 --> 00:05:16.149 align:middle line:84%
They're saying, we're
at this critical time,

00:05:16.149 --> 00:05:18.485 align:middle line:84%
this critical time in
the history of our world

00:05:18.485 --> 00:05:21.454 align:middle line:84%
where the way that we
have lived is changing.

00:05:21.454 --> 00:05:24.191 align:middle line:84%
And to address the crises
that are being created,

00:05:24.191 --> 00:05:26.193 align:middle line:84%
we've got to think
differently than we have ever

00:05:26.193 --> 00:05:27.594 align:middle line:90%
thought of ourselves before.

00:05:27.594 --> 00:05:30.030 align:middle line:84%
And we've got to change the
thinking very, very quickly.

00:05:30.030 --> 00:05:31.398 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And why
this is important

00:05:31.398 --> 00:05:33.066 align:middle line:84%
is because, at this
particular time,

00:05:33.066 --> 00:05:35.569 align:middle line:84%
we hear all this information,
mixed information,

00:05:35.569 --> 00:05:38.538 align:middle line:84%
about global warming and then
there's the economic meltdown

00:05:38.538 --> 00:05:40.574 align:middle line:84%
and there's our entire
corporate crisis.

00:05:40.574 --> 00:05:43.810 align:middle line:84%
There's so much going on that's
affecting each individual

00:05:43.810 --> 00:05:46.546 align:middle line:84%
on an individual basis, in their
family's home life, whatever.

00:05:46.546 --> 00:05:47.480 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Well, it is.

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:49.316 align:middle line:84%
And this is what they
were telling us about.

00:05:49.316 --> 00:05:52.819 align:middle line:84%
They talked about how we
deal with climate change,

00:05:52.819 --> 00:05:56.957 align:middle line:84%
our inability to grow food to
feed the seven plus billion

00:05:56.957 --> 00:05:59.192 align:middle line:84%
people on the planet right
now, the disappearing

00:05:59.192 --> 00:06:01.328 align:middle line:84%
of vital resources
like fresh water

00:06:01.328 --> 00:06:04.698 align:middle line:84%
and food, the collapse,
the inevitable collapse,

00:06:04.698 --> 00:06:05.599 align:middle line:90%
of the global economy.

00:06:05.599 --> 00:06:10.337 align:middle line:84%
2005, they knew it was coming
because the systems that

00:06:10.337 --> 00:06:14.574 align:middle line:84%
were in place at that time
were unsustainable systems.

00:06:14.574 --> 00:06:16.009 align:middle line:90%
And this is what we're seeing.

00:06:16.009 --> 00:06:17.911 align:middle line:84%
When we look at the
world and the things that

00:06:17.911 --> 00:06:19.279 align:middle line:84%
are changing, for
many people it looks

00:06:19.279 --> 00:06:21.114 align:middle line:84%
like everything's coming
apart at the seams.

00:06:21.114 --> 00:06:24.084 align:middle line:84%
If we look closely, what we see
is the only things coming apart

00:06:24.084 --> 00:06:26.486 align:middle line:84%
are the unsustainable
ways of living

00:06:26.486 --> 00:06:28.788 align:middle line:84%
based on unsustainable
ways of thinking.

00:06:28.788 --> 00:06:31.024 align:middle line:84%
And the new discoveries,
now, are telling us

00:06:31.024 --> 00:06:33.659 align:middle line:84%
where we can shift and
giving us very good reasons

00:06:33.659 --> 00:06:34.561 align:middle line:90%
to make those changes.

00:06:34.561 --> 00:06:36.630 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, in fact,
this is really no surprise.

00:06:36.630 --> 00:06:38.064 align:middle line:84%
And as you have
learned and you're

00:06:38.064 --> 00:06:39.699 align:middle line:84%
going to tell us
about today, that this

00:06:39.699 --> 00:06:41.868 align:middle line:90%
is a repeated cycle in history.

00:06:41.868 --> 00:06:42.534 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: It is.

00:06:42.534 --> 00:06:44.471 align:middle line:84%
And I was trained as
a scientist, Lisa,

00:06:44.471 --> 00:06:45.639 align:middle line:90%
and I think science is good.

00:06:45.639 --> 00:06:47.207 align:middle line:84%
Science doesn't have
all the answers.

00:06:47.207 --> 00:06:50.543 align:middle line:84%
But my scientific mind was
asking the question, why now?

00:06:50.543 --> 00:06:52.712 align:middle line:84%
Why would all these changes
be happening right now?

00:06:52.712 --> 00:06:54.214 align:middle line:84%
And what we're
beginning understand

00:06:54.214 --> 00:06:56.283 align:middle line:84%
is that many of the
changes are actually

00:06:56.283 --> 00:06:59.185 align:middle line:84%
triggered by Earth's
location in space.

00:06:59.185 --> 00:07:01.154 align:middle line:84%
It's things like the
tilt and the wobble

00:07:01.154 --> 00:07:02.422 align:middle line:90%
and the angle and the orbit.

00:07:02.422 --> 00:07:05.292 align:middle line:84%
Earth is a very dynamic
body in the heavens.

00:07:05.292 --> 00:07:08.194 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't just rotate
to create night and day

00:07:08.194 --> 00:07:09.329 align:middle line:90%
and tilt for the seasons.

00:07:09.329 --> 00:07:11.398 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot more
going on, but some

00:07:11.398 --> 00:07:13.633 align:middle line:84%
of the cycles that
define these things cover

00:07:13.633 --> 00:07:17.337 align:middle line:84%
such vast periods of
time, no one in our time

00:07:17.337 --> 00:07:19.239 align:middle line:84%
remembers the last
time that it happened.

00:07:19.239 --> 00:07:22.108 align:middle line:84%
And this where-- this is where
our ancient and indigenous

00:07:22.108 --> 00:07:23.877 align:middle line:90%
traditions are so valuable.

00:07:23.877 --> 00:07:26.146 align:middle line:84%
Because they have
carried, perpetuated

00:07:26.146 --> 00:07:27.647 align:middle line:90%
the story of these changes.

00:07:27.647 --> 00:07:30.082 align:middle line:84%
So our own science
now is, in fact,

00:07:30.082 --> 00:07:31.584 align:middle line:84%
telling us that
changes are upon us.

00:07:31.584 --> 00:07:33.720 align:middle line:84%
Interestingly,
they parallel many

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:37.290 align:middle line:84%
of the traditions of our most
cherished ancient indigenous

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:38.258 align:middle line:90%
traditions.

00:07:38.258 --> 00:07:39.893 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Which we'd
love to learn about.

00:07:39.893 --> 00:07:41.561 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well,
some of those-- I

00:07:41.561 --> 00:07:44.230 align:middle line:84%
think we've all heard of
native traditions that

00:07:44.230 --> 00:07:45.265 align:middle line:90%
talk about changes.

00:07:45.265 --> 00:07:47.600 align:middle line:84%
And many of those are
from native cultures

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:48.768 align:middle line:90%
that are close to the earth.

00:07:48.768 --> 00:07:50.437 align:middle line:84%
So they talk about
when a white buffalo

00:07:50.437 --> 00:07:52.339 align:middle line:84%
is born in the plains
of North America,

00:07:52.339 --> 00:07:54.641 align:middle line:84%
or when the crops no longer
grow in their season.

00:07:54.641 --> 00:07:57.143 align:middle line:84%
And for a scientist,
that's not very scientific.

00:07:57.143 --> 00:07:59.446 align:middle line:84%
But we like the Maya
a lot because the Maya

00:07:59.446 --> 00:08:01.114 align:middle line:90%
thought a lot the way we think.

00:08:01.114 --> 00:08:04.084 align:middle line:84%
The Maya talked
about cycles of time

00:08:04.084 --> 00:08:07.520 align:middle line:84%
based in astronomical
events and celestial cycles

00:08:07.520 --> 00:08:09.923 align:middle line:84%
that we can confirm on
our computers today.

00:08:09.923 --> 00:08:12.992 align:middle line:84%
So they are talking a
language of mathematics

00:08:12.992 --> 00:08:13.760 align:middle line:90%
that we understand.

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:16.262 align:middle line:84%
And what the Maya told us-- if
you're looking at your screen

00:08:16.262 --> 00:08:19.766 align:middle line:84%
right now, the Maya told
us about cycles of time.

00:08:19.766 --> 00:08:22.102 align:middle line:84%
Many people believe that
the image on the screen

00:08:22.102 --> 00:08:23.336 align:middle line:90%
is the Mayan calendar.

00:08:23.336 --> 00:08:23.937 align:middle line:90%
And it is not.

00:08:23.937 --> 00:08:25.405 align:middle line:84%
I want to be very
clear about that.

00:08:25.405 --> 00:08:29.042 align:middle line:84%
This is the Aztec calendar
that is based on Mayan ideas.

00:08:29.042 --> 00:08:31.077 align:middle line:84%
But there is no
single artifact that

00:08:31.077 --> 00:08:32.912 align:middle line:84%
represents all
the different ways

00:08:32.912 --> 00:08:35.181 align:middle line:84%
that the Maya were
able to track time.

00:08:35.181 --> 00:08:38.485 align:middle line:84%
But what we're seeing
on the Aztec calendar--

00:08:38.485 --> 00:08:41.354 align:middle line:84%
the four boxes that you see
highlighted in your screen

00:08:41.354 --> 00:08:46.126 align:middle line:84%
represent four cycles
of time in the past

00:08:46.126 --> 00:08:48.661 align:middle line:84%
that parallel the cycles
that we're having now.

00:08:48.661 --> 00:08:51.498 align:middle line:84%
What they said is
every 5,125 years

00:08:51.498 --> 00:08:52.665 align:middle line:90%
we go through a big change.

00:08:52.665 --> 00:08:55.969 align:middle line:90%
It is called a great world age.

00:08:55.969 --> 00:08:58.705 align:middle line:84%
And that we are nearing the
end of a great world age.

00:08:58.705 --> 00:08:59.939 align:middle line:90%
It's not the end of the world.

00:08:59.939 --> 00:09:01.107 align:middle line:90%
It's the end of a world age.

00:09:01.107 --> 00:09:03.443 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: How did they know that?

00:09:03.443 --> 00:09:06.312 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: How did they know
without computers, GPS,

00:09:06.312 --> 00:09:07.046 align:middle line:90%
and satellite?

00:09:07.046 --> 00:09:07.614 align:middle line:84%
So that's one of
the great mysteries.

00:09:07.614 --> 00:09:08.915 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And archeological digs.

00:09:08.915 --> 00:09:10.116 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: We could do a
whole program on that.

00:09:10.116 --> 00:09:10.417 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:09:10.417 --> 00:09:10.683 align:middle line:90%
It's amazing.

00:09:10.683 --> 00:09:12.185 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And there's
some very good theories

00:09:12.185 --> 00:09:14.687 align:middle line:84%
that we're going to talk about
as we go through our program.

00:09:14.687 --> 00:09:17.123 align:middle line:84%
The fact is they did
understand cycles in their time

00:09:17.123 --> 00:09:19.125 align:middle line:84%
that we're only beginning
to understand in ours.

00:09:19.125 --> 00:09:21.795 align:middle line:84%
And they told us in the language
of their time, a language

00:09:21.795 --> 00:09:23.530 align:middle line:84%
that's only now
beginning to make sense.

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:24.831 align:middle line:90%
[CLEARS THROAT] Excuse me.

00:09:24.831 --> 00:09:27.534 align:middle line:84%
So they told us about
four cycles in the past,

00:09:27.534 --> 00:09:30.270 align:middle line:90%
5,125 years long.

00:09:30.270 --> 00:09:34.274 align:middle line:84%
And they told us that we are
living the fifth and final

00:09:34.274 --> 00:09:36.910 align:middle line:84%
in a series of five
of these cycles.

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:39.779 align:middle line:84%
We're living this
cycle right now.

00:09:39.779 --> 00:09:41.915 align:middle line:84%
And that this cycle would
end in our lifetime.

00:09:41.915 --> 00:09:45.084 align:middle line:84%
That this cycle began with
a rare astronomical event,

00:09:45.084 --> 00:09:47.454 align:middle line:90%
August 11, 3114 BC.

00:09:47.454 --> 00:09:49.055 align:middle line:90%
This is the biblical era.

00:09:49.055 --> 00:09:52.225 align:middle line:84%
Interestingly, it's when so
many of our spiritual traditions

00:09:52.225 --> 00:09:54.594 align:middle line:84%
were created to help people
deal with the changes--

00:09:54.594 --> 00:09:55.428 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:09:55.428 --> 00:09:56.729 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --in their
lives then, very

00:09:56.729 --> 00:09:58.398 align:middle line:84%
similar to what we're
living right now.

00:09:58.398 --> 00:09:59.966 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So religion
in those types

00:09:59.966 --> 00:10:03.803 align:middle line:84%
of contexts happened because
of the confusion that

00:10:03.803 --> 00:10:04.938 align:middle line:90%
was happening at that time.

00:10:04.938 --> 00:10:06.673 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: At least, they
happened at the same time.

00:10:06.673 --> 00:10:08.408 align:middle line:84%
What we can say is
in response to what

00:10:08.408 --> 00:10:12.779 align:middle line:84%
was happening-- so the cycle
began August 11, 3114 BC.

00:10:12.779 --> 00:10:18.685 align:middle line:84%
They told us that this cycle
would end precisely 1,872,000

00:10:18.685 --> 00:10:23.823 align:middle line:84%
days later-- that is
5,125 years later--

00:10:23.823 --> 00:10:28.895 align:middle line:84%
with another rare astronomical
event that occurs on the winter

00:10:28.895 --> 00:10:31.598 align:middle line:84%
solstice, December
21 of the year 2012.

00:10:31.598 --> 00:10:32.365 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: 2012, yeah.

00:10:32.365 --> 00:10:34.701 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: So this is where
this date comes from.

00:10:34.701 --> 00:10:37.470 align:middle line:84%
It's not a date that
just is made up or comes,

00:10:37.470 --> 00:10:39.339 align:middle line:84%
you know, we just
pulled out of the air--

00:10:39.339 --> 00:10:40.673 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: From movies, yeah.

00:10:40.673 --> 00:10:43.443 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: It is linked
directly to astronomical cycles

00:10:43.443 --> 00:10:45.478 align:middle line:90%
that we can confirm today.

00:10:45.478 --> 00:10:48.214 align:middle line:84%
And what they told us-- and
this is very, very important--

00:10:48.214 --> 00:10:49.949 align:middle line:84%
they didn't say it's
the end of the world.

00:10:49.949 --> 00:10:51.684 align:middle line:84%
They said that it's
the end of a world age

00:10:51.684 --> 00:10:54.454 align:middle line:84%
and that anything that
was not sustainable,

00:10:54.454 --> 00:10:56.823 align:middle line:84%
that our way of
life would change.

00:10:56.823 --> 00:10:58.858 align:middle line:84%
They didn't say that
the world would end.

00:10:58.858 --> 00:11:00.793 align:middle line:84%
And there's no scientific
evidence, in fact,

00:11:00.793 --> 00:11:03.329 align:middle line:84%
to support the theories
that the world is ending

00:11:03.329 --> 00:11:04.831 align:middle line:84%
and many people are
putting forward.

00:11:04.831 --> 00:11:05.398 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:11:05.398 --> 00:11:07.200 align:middle line:84%
And what I love
about this is this

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:11.538 align:middle line:84%
is evidence that has existed for
hundreds and hundreds of years.

00:11:11.538 --> 00:11:13.806 align:middle line:84%
And just because--
it's so interesting

00:11:13.806 --> 00:11:17.443 align:middle line:84%
that this time in history
has been predicted.

00:11:17.443 --> 00:11:20.213 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: It's been predicted,
prophesized, feared, embraced,

00:11:20.213 --> 00:11:22.115 align:middle line:90%
depending on your perspective.

00:11:22.115 --> 00:11:24.517 align:middle line:84%
But the key is, in
our culture, we've

00:11:24.517 --> 00:11:28.054 align:middle line:84%
been taught to think in
a linear perspective, led

00:11:28.054 --> 00:11:30.623 align:middle line:84%
to believe that we live-- that
our civilization is linear.

00:11:30.623 --> 00:11:32.592 align:middle line:84%
It happened once in the
primitive civilization,

00:11:32.592 --> 00:11:35.628 align:middle line:84%
and now here we are at the
pinnacle of the sophistication

00:11:35.628 --> 00:11:36.696 align:middle line:90%
that we have today and--

00:11:36.696 --> 00:11:38.298 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, because
science is relatively young.

00:11:38.298 --> 00:11:39.665 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: It is
relatively young.

00:11:39.665 --> 00:11:41.267 align:middle line:84%
Science is only
about 300 years old.

00:11:41.267 --> 00:11:42.835 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That is young
in this overall-

00:11:42.835 --> 00:11:44.003 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Science is good.

00:11:44.003 --> 00:11:45.705 align:middle line:84%
Like I say, I was
trained as a scientist.

00:11:45.705 --> 00:11:48.274 align:middle line:84%
But we know that science
doesn't have all the answers.

00:11:48.274 --> 00:11:53.880 align:middle line:84%
Science can only be as useful to
us as we allow it to be honest.

00:11:53.880 --> 00:11:55.815 align:middle line:84%
And to keep science
honest, we must

00:11:55.815 --> 00:11:58.484 align:middle line:84%
allow the scientific
story of our lives

00:11:58.484 --> 00:12:01.521 align:middle line:84%
and our world to be updated
with new discoveries

00:12:01.521 --> 00:12:03.556 align:middle line:84%
when they are
proven to be facts.

00:12:03.556 --> 00:12:05.725 align:middle line:84%
And this is where we're
running into problems today.

00:12:05.725 --> 00:12:09.395 align:middle line:84%
There's a scientific story
that is about 150 years old,

00:12:09.395 --> 00:12:12.198 align:middle line:84%
about us, where we come from,
our relationship to the Earth,

00:12:12.198 --> 00:12:15.335 align:middle line:84%
our relationship to our
bodies, our relationship

00:12:15.335 --> 00:12:16.836 align:middle line:90%
to civilization.

00:12:16.836 --> 00:12:20.473 align:middle line:84%
And that story, as we're going
to see in just a few minutes,

00:12:20.473 --> 00:12:22.875 align:middle line:84%
is based on a number
of false assumptions.

00:12:22.875 --> 00:12:24.611 align:middle line:84%
Now that new discoveries
are overturning

00:12:24.611 --> 00:12:26.646 align:middle line:84%
those false assumptions,
it gives us good reasons

00:12:26.646 --> 00:12:27.547 align:middle line:90%
to think differently.

00:12:27.547 --> 00:12:31.284 align:middle line:84%
But somehow our ancestors knew
that these cycles were coming.

00:12:31.284 --> 00:12:35.021 align:middle line:84%
Our own science now is
beginning to confirm these.

00:12:35.021 --> 00:12:38.324 align:middle line:84%
And one of the places--
I wanted our viewers

00:12:38.324 --> 00:12:41.294 align:middle line:84%
to see this-- the ice
caps of our planet

00:12:41.294 --> 00:12:43.696 align:middle line:84%
are virtual libraries of
the history of our world.

00:12:43.696 --> 00:12:44.564 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Mmm, amazing.

00:12:44.564 --> 00:12:46.232 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Every year,
a new layer of ice

00:12:46.232 --> 00:12:48.301 align:middle line:84%
is deposited that has a
record of the climate,

00:12:48.301 --> 00:12:50.803 align:middle line:84%
the dust, the pollen,
little bubbles

00:12:50.803 --> 00:12:52.405 align:middle line:84%
of carbon dioxide
from the atmosphere.

00:12:52.405 --> 00:12:53.673 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: For thousands of years.

00:12:53.673 --> 00:12:55.942 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well, in
1999, the scientist

00:12:55.942 --> 00:12:57.644 align:middle line:84%
of the earth got
together and drilled

00:12:57.644 --> 00:12:59.145 align:middle line:84%
through the thickest
part of the ice

00:12:59.145 --> 00:13:01.280 align:middle line:84%
to preserve the
record that's there.

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:02.482 align:middle line:90%
Because the ice is melting.

00:13:02.482 --> 00:13:05.084 align:middle line:84%
They wanted to preserve as much
as they could before it melts.

00:13:05.084 --> 00:13:07.453 align:middle line:84%
And to their amazement--
now, each layer

00:13:07.453 --> 00:13:09.956 align:middle line:84%
represents one year of
the history of the Earth.

00:13:09.956 --> 00:13:11.991 align:middle line:84%
And even the scientists,
I think were amazed.

00:13:11.991 --> 00:13:13.493 align:middle line:84%
Because when these
cores came up,

00:13:13.493 --> 00:13:19.699 align:middle line:90%
Lisa, 450,000 layers of ice.

00:13:19.699 --> 00:13:23.002 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: 450,000 layers, years.

00:13:23.002 --> 00:13:24.737 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Each
layer is one year.

00:13:24.737 --> 00:13:26.239 align:middle line:90%
450,000--

00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:26.806 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Years.

00:13:26.806 --> 00:13:28.207 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --years of the
history of the Earth.

00:13:28.207 --> 00:13:29.142 align:middle line:90%
Suddenly, we have--

00:13:29.142 --> 00:13:29.475 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --of evidence.

00:13:29.475 --> 00:13:31.511 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --to compare to where
we are right now, to find out,

00:13:31.511 --> 00:13:32.278 align:middle line:90%
is Earth broken?

00:13:32.278 --> 00:13:33.112 align:middle line:90%
Have we broken it?

00:13:33.112 --> 00:13:35.081 align:middle line:84%
Are we living an
anomalous cycle?

00:13:35.081 --> 00:13:37.583 align:middle line:84%
And the answers to that are
driving many or the discoveries

00:13:37.583 --> 00:13:38.885 align:middle line:90%
that we're talking about today.

00:13:38.885 --> 00:13:40.953 align:middle line:84%
So if our viewers have
never seen ice cores,

00:13:40.953 --> 00:13:42.622 align:middle line:84%
I want you to see what
an ice core looks like.

00:13:42.622 --> 00:13:43.856 align:middle line:90%
It's on your screen right now.

00:13:43.856 --> 00:13:44.991 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: This is fascinating.

00:13:44.991 --> 00:13:45.992 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Yes, go ahead.

00:13:45.992 --> 00:13:50.163 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And this was
discovered in 1999.

00:13:50.163 --> 00:13:53.966 align:middle line:84%
It's amazing that it hasn't
hit mass mainstream media.

00:13:53.966 --> 00:13:56.202 align:middle line:84%
I mean, look at all of the
history that's right there.

00:13:56.202 --> 00:13:57.170 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well, from
these ice cores,

00:13:57.170 --> 00:13:59.205 align:middle line:84%
we can tell a lot about
the history of the Earth.

00:13:59.205 --> 00:14:02.341 align:middle line:84%
We can talk about temperature,
about ancient sea levels,

00:14:02.341 --> 00:14:04.177 align:middle line:84%
the strength of the sun
reaching the earth--

00:14:04.177 --> 00:14:04.444 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:14:04.444 --> 00:14:06.245 align:middle line:10%
>>BRADEN: --the magnetic field
of the Earth, all those things.

00:14:06.245 --> 00:14:08.448 align:middle line:10%
So what I'd like for
our viewers to see,

00:14:08.448 --> 00:14:11.084 align:middle line:10%
there's a screen-- an image
on your screen right now.

00:14:11.084 --> 00:14:12.351 align:middle line:10%
To the left is present day.

00:14:12.351 --> 00:14:14.587 align:middle line:10%
To the right is
450,000 years ago.

00:14:14.587 --> 00:14:16.122 align:middle line:10%
All I'd like for
you to see from this

00:14:16.122 --> 00:14:18.491 align:middle line:10%
is that there are obvious
cycles that are happening.

00:14:18.491 --> 00:14:20.593 align:middle line:10%
And we can definitely
see these cycles.

00:14:20.593 --> 00:14:24.697 align:middle line:10%
And the cycles are about
100,000 years a piece.

00:14:24.697 --> 00:14:27.233 align:middle line:10%
The graph on top
is one ice core.

00:14:27.233 --> 00:14:29.802 align:middle line:10%
The one in the middle, the
green, is a second ice core.

00:14:29.802 --> 00:14:31.370 align:middle line:10%
You can see they
parallel one another.

00:14:31.370 --> 00:14:33.473 align:middle line:10%
The one on the bottom is
the thickness of the ice.

