00:16:01.961 --> 00:16:05.298 align:middle line:84%
And then, it goes into the
next portion of the cycle.

00:16:05.298 --> 00:16:08.000 align:middle line:84%
So what this says
to me is that I'm

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.703 align:middle line:84%
less concerned about the
physical changes in our world

00:16:10.703 --> 00:16:11.204 align:middle line:90%
today.

00:16:11.204 --> 00:16:12.438 align:middle line:84%
Our ancestors
lived through them.

00:16:12.438 --> 00:16:13.239 align:middle line:90%
They wrote to us.

00:16:13.239 --> 00:16:15.608 align:middle line:84%
They told us in the
language of their time

00:16:15.608 --> 00:16:18.044 align:middle line:84%
what we would need to do to
work through these cycles.

00:16:18.044 --> 00:16:19.412 align:middle line:84%
Now, our own
science is beginning

00:16:19.412 --> 00:16:21.747 align:middle line:84%
to confirm what our
ancestors told us.

00:16:21.747 --> 00:16:24.116 align:middle line:84%
And it's all about our
relationship to cooperation

00:16:24.116 --> 00:16:26.252 align:middle line:84%
and competition and the
way deal with problems,

00:16:26.252 --> 00:16:28.487 align:middle line:84%
the way we solve problems
in our lives today.

00:16:28.487 --> 00:16:30.056 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This is
very, very important.

00:16:30.056 --> 00:16:32.425 align:middle line:84%
Because we are-- this
cycle has been predicted.

00:16:32.425 --> 00:16:35.061 align:middle line:84%
It is-- We're in the
right time in the cycle

00:16:35.061 --> 00:16:37.129 align:middle line:84%
if you know enough about
what we're talking about.

00:16:37.129 --> 00:16:37.630 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Sure.

00:16:37.630 --> 00:16:39.465 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And that's why
this is so important.

00:16:39.465 --> 00:16:41.300 align:middle line:84%
And what we can really
do to affect it.

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:43.903 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well, it is actually--
rather than viewing the Earth

00:16:43.903 --> 00:16:48.374 align:middle line:84%
as being broken, it's actually
a rare, precious, pivotal moment

00:16:48.374 --> 00:16:51.344 align:middle line:84%
and opportunity to
change the things

00:16:51.344 --> 00:16:53.446 align:middle line:90%
in the past that no longer work.

00:16:53.446 --> 00:16:54.814 align:middle line:90%
It's a reality check, Lisa.

00:16:54.814 --> 00:16:55.848 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, we're
seeing that everywhere.

00:16:55.848 --> 00:16:57.083 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: The things
we've done that no longer

00:16:57.083 --> 00:16:58.251 align:middle line:90%
work, let's stop doing them.

00:16:58.251 --> 00:17:00.553 align:middle line:84%
And the things that we've
done that work well, let's

00:17:00.553 --> 00:17:01.254 align:middle line:90%
do a lot of them.

00:17:01.254 --> 00:17:02.321 align:middle line:90%
Are there systems broken?

00:17:02.321 --> 00:17:02.822 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:17:02.822 --> 00:17:04.857 align:middle line:84%
And there are a lot of
beautiful things happening

00:17:04.857 --> 00:17:08.895 align:middle line:84%
in the world and a very,
very beautiful opportunity

00:17:08.895 --> 00:17:12.498 align:middle line:84%
to embrace and bring
those new systems forward,

00:17:12.498 --> 00:17:14.500 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the
healing of our bodies,

00:17:14.500 --> 00:17:17.069 align:middle line:84%
our relationship to our food,
the way we live our lives.

00:17:17.069 --> 00:17:18.671 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And with our families
and our work and everything.

00:17:18.671 --> 00:17:19.005 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Absolutely.

00:17:19.005 --> 00:17:20.138 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So what did
it all stem from?

00:17:20.138 --> 00:17:22.174 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well, when I
wrote the book Deep Truth,

00:17:22.174 --> 00:17:24.743 align:middle line:84%
one of the questions
that I wanted

00:17:24.743 --> 00:17:26.811 align:middle line:84%
to answer for
myself is why do we

00:17:26.811 --> 00:17:28.881 align:middle line:84%
think about ourselves
the way we do?

00:17:28.881 --> 00:17:30.616 align:middle line:84%
And how do we
solve these crises?

00:17:30.616 --> 00:17:33.085 align:middle line:84%
And what became very
apparent is that the way

00:17:33.085 --> 00:17:35.521 align:middle line:84%
that we answer a single
question determines

00:17:35.521 --> 00:17:36.722 align:middle line:90%
how we solve our crises.

00:17:36.722 --> 00:17:38.925 align:middle line:84%
And the question is
simply this, who are we?

00:17:38.925 --> 00:17:39.625 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Mmm, yes.

00:17:39.625 --> 00:17:42.595 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Or who am I? --when
we think about ourselves.

00:17:42.595 --> 00:17:45.698 align:middle line:84%
That seemingly innocent,
very benign little question

00:17:45.698 --> 00:17:47.733 align:middle line:84%
is actually the
filter through which

00:17:47.733 --> 00:17:49.969 align:middle line:84%
we will create all
of the decisions

00:17:49.969 --> 00:17:51.404 align:middle line:84%
and all of the
choices to address

00:17:51.404 --> 00:17:53.940 align:middle line:84%
every personal or
collective crisis.

00:17:53.940 --> 00:17:54.607 align:middle line:90%
Who are we?

00:17:54.607 --> 00:17:56.075 align:middle line:84%
And where does that
idea come from?

00:17:56.075 --> 00:17:57.877 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And where are we
going into the future?

00:17:57.877 --> 00:17:58.644 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Absolutely.

00:17:58.644 --> 00:17:59.512 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --personally, as well.

00:17:59.512 --> 00:18:00.379 align:middle line:90%
What are our goals?

00:18:00.379 --> 00:18:01.213 align:middle line:90%
What are our dreams?

00:18:01.213 --> 00:18:01.714 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:18:01.714 --> 00:18:02.515 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Yeah.

00:18:02.515 --> 00:18:06.285 align:middle line:84%
And it's all based, however, on
the way we think of ourselves.

00:18:06.285 --> 00:18:09.655 align:middle line:84%
And rarely do we have the
opportunity to really, really

00:18:09.655 --> 00:18:11.390 align:middle line:84%
embrace that and
think about that.

00:18:11.390 --> 00:18:14.360 align:middle line:84%
Well, when we do think
about that, what we find

00:18:14.360 --> 00:18:16.429 align:middle line:84%
is that much of our
lives and our world today

00:18:16.429 --> 00:18:18.364 align:middle line:84%
is based on scientific
assumptions, some

00:18:18.364 --> 00:18:20.700 align:middle line:90%
of them 150 years old.

00:18:20.700 --> 00:18:21.667 align:middle line:90%
There are many of them.

00:18:21.667 --> 00:18:23.135 align:middle line:84%
I've identified
five in the book.

00:18:23.135 --> 00:18:25.871 align:middle line:84%
I'd like to share them with
our viewers right now, quickly.

00:18:25.871 --> 00:18:26.038 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:18:26.038 --> 00:18:27.039 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And then, zero
in on the one that's

00:18:27.039 --> 00:18:28.674 align:middle line:84%
having, I believe, the
greatest impact today.

00:18:28.674 --> 00:18:30.242 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So think
about these as things

00:18:30.242 --> 00:18:32.712 align:middle line:84%
that shape our societies,
that shape our belief

00:18:32.712 --> 00:18:33.779 align:middle line:90%
systems, really.

00:18:33.779 --> 00:18:36.382 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: So if you're looking
at your screen right now,

00:18:36.382 --> 00:18:37.683 align:middle line:84%
what you're seeing--
when you were in school,

00:18:37.683 --> 00:18:40.052 align:middle line:84%
Lisa, when I was in school,
young people in school today,

00:18:40.052 --> 00:18:43.055 align:middle line:84%
we're being taught these
assumptions as facts.

00:18:43.055 --> 00:18:45.858 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to see
that they are not facts,

00:18:45.858 --> 00:18:46.692 align:middle line:90%
as a matter of fact.

00:18:46.692 --> 00:18:47.159 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:18:47.159 --> 00:18:48.894 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: The first
one is that evolution

00:18:48.894 --> 00:18:50.196 align:middle line:90%
explains life in general.

00:18:50.196 --> 00:18:52.131 align:middle line:90%
It explains human life.

00:18:52.131 --> 00:18:55.167 align:middle line:84%
The second assumption is
that civilization itself,

00:18:55.167 --> 00:18:57.536 align:middle line:84%
it's about 5,000
or 5,500 years old,

00:18:57.536 --> 00:18:59.972 align:middle line:84%
that it's happened one time
and it's essentially linear--

00:18:59.972 --> 00:19:00.673 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That that's it, OK.

00:19:00.673 --> 00:19:02.508 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --from primitive
to sophisticated.

00:19:02.508 --> 00:19:04.477 align:middle line:10%
Number three is that
consciousness is somehow

00:19:04.477 --> 00:19:06.712 align:middle line:10%
separate from our
physical world.

00:19:06.712 --> 00:19:10.182 align:middle line:84%
Number four is related, that the
space between physical things

00:19:10.182 --> 00:19:10.850 align:middle line:90%
is empty.

00:19:10.850 --> 00:19:13.986 align:middle line:10%
And number five is a Darwinian,
another Darwinian assumption,

00:19:13.986 --> 00:19:16.455 align:middle line:10%
that nature is based
on what he called

00:19:16.455 --> 00:19:17.623 align:middle line:10%
"survival of the strongest."

00:19:17.623 --> 00:19:19.392 align:middle line:10%
It later became
survival of the fittest.

00:19:19.392 --> 00:19:21.227 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: And that has
become a big buzz word.

00:19:21.227 --> 00:19:22.895 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: And his own words.

00:19:22.895 --> 00:19:25.631 align:middle line:84%
All of these are taught
in our schools today.

00:19:25.631 --> 00:19:27.466 align:middle line:84%
All of them are
absolutely false.

00:19:27.466 --> 00:19:29.135 align:middle line:84%
They've been proven
scientifically

00:19:29.135 --> 00:19:31.604 align:middle line:84%
in peer reviewed,
technical journals.

00:19:31.604 --> 00:19:32.438 align:middle line:90%
These are false.

00:19:32.438 --> 00:19:36.275 align:middle line:84%
The evolution explains
life, not human life.

00:19:36.275 --> 00:19:38.844 align:middle line:84%
And in longer programs, we can
get into that in more detail.

00:19:38.844 --> 00:19:39.545 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Right

00:19:39.545 --> 00:19:40.913 align:middle line:10%
>>BRADEN: But what I'd like
to do right now, if you're

00:19:40.913 --> 00:19:42.982 align:middle line:10%
taking notes, write
false above all these.

00:19:42.982 --> 00:19:44.517 align:middle line:10%
Put a circle and a big
line right through that.

00:19:44.517 --> 00:19:45.851 align:middle line:10%
And let's zero in
on the one that's

00:19:45.851 --> 00:19:46.685 align:middle line:10%
having the greatest impact--

00:19:46.685 --> 00:19:47.953 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Kids at home,
tell your teachers, false.

00:19:47.953 --> 00:19:48.888 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: --on our lives today.

00:19:48.888 --> 00:19:50.589 align:middle line:84%
If you wonder, if
you're saying, well why

00:19:50.589 --> 00:19:51.857 align:middle line:90%
are these things important?

00:19:51.857 --> 00:19:54.126 align:middle line:84%
These are assumptions that
we now know are false.

00:19:54.126 --> 00:19:56.162 align:middle line:84%
And if you want to know
what the consequences

00:19:56.162 --> 00:19:57.930 align:middle line:84%
of these false
assumptions are, we

00:19:57.930 --> 00:19:59.832 align:middle line:84%
need look no further
than the world around us,

00:19:59.832 --> 00:20:02.368 align:middle line:84%
how we deal with climate
change and the failing

00:20:02.368 --> 00:20:04.837 align:middle line:84%
economic system, how we deal
with the food and the water

00:20:04.837 --> 00:20:07.106 align:middle line:84%
shortages and
disease, how we deal

00:20:07.106 --> 00:20:09.175 align:middle line:90%
with the crises of our time.

00:20:09.175 --> 00:20:12.344 align:middle line:84%
Now, when we look at these
false assumptions, the idea

00:20:12.344 --> 00:20:14.814 align:middle line:84%
that nature is based upon
survival of the strongest,

00:20:14.814 --> 00:20:16.849 align:middle line:84%
this I think is so
deeply entrenched, Lisa--

00:20:16.849 --> 00:20:17.416 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It is.

00:20:17.416 --> 00:20:19.985 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --in ways that either
consciously or unconsciously,

00:20:19.985 --> 00:20:21.320 align:middle line:90%
you may not even be aware of.

00:20:21.320 --> 00:20:23.689 align:middle line:84%
I'd like for our viewers to
know where this came from.

00:20:23.689 --> 00:20:26.025 align:middle line:84%
So I'm pulling this right
out of Darwin's book.

00:20:26.025 --> 00:20:28.260 align:middle line:10%
This is from his book On
the Origin of Species,

00:20:28.260 --> 00:20:30.396 align:middle line:10%
published in 1859.

00:20:30.396 --> 00:20:33.833 align:middle line:84%
What Darwin said, he looked
in the world around him.

00:20:33.833 --> 00:20:37.269 align:middle line:84%
And when he saw examples in
nature of certain insects

00:20:37.269 --> 00:20:39.538 align:middle line:84%
or animals and the way
they behaved there,

00:20:39.538 --> 00:20:41.173 align:middle line:84%
he extrapolated
that and said, that

00:20:41.173 --> 00:20:44.777 align:middle line:84%
must be the law for all nature
everywhere, including humans.

00:20:44.777 --> 00:20:46.112 align:middle line:90%
So I'm going to share his quote.

00:20:46.112 --> 00:20:47.179 align:middle line:90%
This is a direct quote.

00:20:47.179 --> 00:20:49.081 align:middle line:84%
He begins by telling
us it may not

00:20:49.081 --> 00:20:50.783 align:middle line:84%
be logical, what
he's about to say.

00:20:50.783 --> 00:20:54.687 align:middle line:84%
So this is what he says, "It
may not be a logical deduction,

00:20:54.687 --> 00:20:58.724 align:middle line:84%
but to my imagination it is
far more satisfactory to look

00:20:58.724 --> 00:21:01.560 align:middle line:84%
at instincts, such as" birds
that the other birds out

00:21:01.560 --> 00:21:03.162 align:middle line:84%
of the nest because
they're different--

00:21:03.162 --> 00:21:03.863 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So he was hypothesizing.

00:21:03.863 --> 00:21:06.098 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: He was-- or
ants making slaves out

00:21:06.098 --> 00:21:06.799 align:middle line:90%
of other ants.

00:21:06.799 --> 00:21:07.900 align:middle line:90%
Because they can do that.

00:21:07.900 --> 00:21:09.568 align:middle line:84%
Because they're
bigger and stronger.

00:21:09.568 --> 00:21:11.437 align:middle line:84%
He said that it
makes sense to him

00:21:11.437 --> 00:21:15.941 align:middle line:84%
to see those as small examples
of a general rule, a law that

00:21:15.941 --> 00:21:16.942 align:middle line:90%
applies to all life.

00:21:16.942 --> 00:21:18.110 align:middle line:90%
And here's his law.

00:21:18.110 --> 00:21:22.548 align:middle line:84%
He said, "The law is multiply,
vary, let the strongest live,

00:21:22.548 --> 00:21:23.949 align:middle line:90%
and the weakest die."

00:21:23.949 --> 00:21:26.485 align:middle line:84%
Let the strongest live
and the weakest die.

00:21:26.485 --> 00:21:28.721 align:middle line:84%
This is such a dangerous
way of thinking.

00:21:28.721 --> 00:21:31.557 align:middle line:84%
Our corporations
today that are failing

00:21:31.557 --> 00:21:32.925 align:middle line:90%
are based upon this concept.

00:21:32.925 --> 00:21:35.594 align:middle line:84%
Our global economic system
is based upon this concept.

00:21:35.594 --> 00:21:38.764 align:middle line:84%
The way that we share
the diminishing resources

00:21:38.764 --> 00:21:41.634 align:middle line:84%
on our planet as we go
through the cyclic shifts

00:21:41.634 --> 00:21:43.869 align:middle line:84%
that we've just identified
in the last segment

00:21:43.869 --> 00:21:46.438 align:middle line:84%
are based on this
way of thinking.

00:21:46.438 --> 00:21:48.407 align:middle line:84%
Our young people
in school are being

00:21:48.407 --> 00:21:51.076 align:middle line:84%
taught that it's more important
to be right and succeed than it

00:21:51.076 --> 00:21:53.979 align:middle line:84%
is to develop the
excellence of--

00:21:53.979 --> 00:21:55.714 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Their personal
excellence, yes.

00:21:55.714 --> 00:21:57.183 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Precisely.

00:21:57.183 --> 00:21:59.919 align:middle line:84%
This idea, survival
of the strongest,

00:21:59.919 --> 00:22:02.922 align:middle line:84%
if we want to know the
consequences of this thinking,

00:22:02.922 --> 00:22:05.691 align:middle line:84%
we need look no further
than the 20th century.

00:22:05.691 --> 00:22:08.427 align:middle line:84%
Some of the greatest atrocities
of human against human

00:22:08.427 --> 00:22:09.995 align:middle line:84%
and the greatest
human suffering were

00:22:09.995 --> 00:22:12.665 align:middle line:84%
justified in this
way of thinking.

00:22:12.665 --> 00:22:14.800 align:middle line:84%
And many of the crises that
we identified earlier--

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:15.634 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The famine--

00:22:15.634 --> 00:22:16.735 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Absolutely.

00:22:16.735 --> 00:22:18.137 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --the
disease, everything.

00:22:18.137 --> 00:22:19.872 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: They're all the
result of this way of thinking.

00:22:19.872 --> 00:22:22.208 align:middle line:84%
Now, the flip side-- and I
want to get to the good news.

00:22:22.208 --> 00:22:24.710 align:middle line:84%
The good news is that new
discoveries are telling us

00:22:24.710 --> 00:22:27.646 align:middle line:84%
that nature is not based upon
survival of the strongest.

00:22:27.646 --> 00:22:31.283 align:middle line:84%
Over 400 peer-reviewed studies
were conduct in the late '90s,

00:22:31.283 --> 00:22:33.752 align:middle line:84%
in the early 2000s,
asking a single question:

00:22:33.752 --> 00:22:37.356 align:middle line:84%
what is the optimum amount of
competition in any environment?

00:22:37.356 --> 00:22:37.990 align:middle line:90%
The classroom?

00:22:37.990 --> 00:22:38.724 align:middle line:90%
The workplace?

00:22:38.724 --> 00:22:39.725 align:middle line:90%
The playing field?

00:22:39.725 --> 00:22:41.060 align:middle line:90%
And this is violent competition.

00:22:41.060 --> 00:22:42.561 align:middle line:84%
This isn't a friendly
game of chess.

00:22:42.561 --> 00:22:43.295 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: All right.

00:22:43.295 --> 00:22:46.031 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And all 400 studies
came back with exactly the same

00:22:46.031 --> 00:22:46.532 align:middle line:90%
answer--

00:22:46.532 --> 00:22:47.566 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: When was this?

00:22:47.566 --> 00:22:49.735 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --the answer
was zero competition.

00:22:49.735 --> 00:22:52.171 align:middle line:84%
This was in the late
'90s, early 2000s.

00:22:52.171 --> 00:22:54.473 align:middle line:84%
Alfie Kohn, in his
book, No Contest:

00:22:54.473 --> 00:22:58.077 align:middle line:84%
The Case Against
Competition, really,

00:22:58.077 --> 00:22:59.311 align:middle line:90%
really brought this to light.

00:22:59.311 --> 00:23:01.747 align:middle line:84%
Now I just want to share
a quote. "The ideal amount

00:23:01.747 --> 00:23:03.949 align:middle line:84%
of competition," he said,
"in any environment,

00:23:03.949 --> 00:23:06.452 align:middle line:84%
the classroom, the workplace,
the family, the playing field,

00:23:06.452 --> 00:23:07.186 align:middle line:90%
is none.

00:23:07.186 --> 00:23:10.656 align:middle line:84%
Competition always, always,
always is destructive."

00:23:10.656 --> 00:23:13.792 align:middle line:10%
That is followed by
another discovery

00:23:13.792 --> 00:23:16.428 align:middle line:10%
in the very prestigious
journal "New Scientist."

00:23:16.428 --> 00:23:18.097 align:middle line:10%
I'm speaking quickly
because I want this

00:23:18.097 --> 00:23:18.931 align:middle line:10%
all in before the break.

00:23:18.931 --> 00:23:19.965 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Well, this
is very important.

00:23:19.965 --> 00:23:22.234 align:middle line:10%
>>BRADEN: "New Scientist,"
this is April, 2008.

00:23:22.234 --> 00:23:24.770 align:middle line:10%
This is a direct quote
from Michael Le Page.

00:23:24.770 --> 00:23:27.740 align:middle line:10%
What he says is, "What
we see in the wild is not

00:23:27.740 --> 00:23:29.408 align:middle line:10%
every animal for itself.

00:23:29.408 --> 00:23:33.712 align:middle line:10%
Cooperation," he said, "is an
incredibly successful survival

00:23:33.712 --> 00:23:34.647 align:middle line:10%
strategy."

00:23:34.647 --> 00:23:37.750 align:middle line:10%
He goes on to say that when
cooperation breaks down,

00:23:37.750 --> 00:23:39.918 align:middle line:10%
the results can be disastrous.

00:23:39.918 --> 00:23:42.955 align:middle line:84%
And just to give our listeners
and our viewers an idea,

00:23:42.955 --> 00:23:45.958 align:middle line:84%
if you want to see a beautiful
example of cooperation,

00:23:45.958 --> 00:23:48.260 align:middle line:84%
you need look no further
than the body that

00:23:48.260 --> 00:23:50.763 align:middle line:84%
houses the soul that is
seeing this broadcast.

00:23:50.763 --> 00:23:53.832 align:middle line:84%
Because your one body
is actually a community,

00:23:53.832 --> 00:23:57.703 align:middle line:84%
as my dear friend and colleague
Dr. Bruce Lipton reminds us,

00:23:57.703 --> 00:24:01.240 align:middle line:84%
50 trillion cells that must
cooperate and work together

00:24:01.240 --> 00:24:03.008 align:middle line:84%
to give us the
bodies that function

00:24:03.008 --> 00:24:04.843 align:middle line:84%
so that we can be
in this world--

00:24:04.843 --> 00:24:05.577 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, and--

00:24:05.577 --> 00:24:07.112 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --if that breaks
down, that is disastrous.

00:24:07.112 --> 00:24:08.314 align:middle line:90%
And that's only one example.

00:24:08.314 --> 00:24:10.482 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: If that breaks down,
that's what disease is.

00:24:10.482 --> 00:24:13.852 align:middle line:84%
And the body is constantly
achieving its highest state.

00:24:13.852 --> 00:24:15.888 align:middle line:84%
It's constantly
repairing, constantly

00:24:15.888 --> 00:24:19.358 align:middle line:84%
trying to regain
that optimal state.

00:24:19.358 --> 00:24:20.526 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Well, it is.

00:24:20.526 --> 00:24:22.761 align:middle line:84%
And this would be important
at any time, Lisa.

00:24:22.761 --> 00:24:25.664 align:middle line:84%
But now, within the
context of where we are,

00:24:25.664 --> 00:24:28.934 align:middle line:84%
we are the generation
living the close

00:24:28.934 --> 00:24:33.439 align:middle line:84%
of a 5,125 year long cycle
and the birth of the next

00:24:33.439 --> 00:24:36.075 align:middle line:84%
that happens to coincide
with some of the greatest

00:24:36.075 --> 00:24:40.179 align:middle line:84%
physical changes on this
planet, wreaking havoc

00:24:40.179 --> 00:24:42.748 align:middle line:90%
upon unsustainable ways of life.

00:24:42.748 --> 00:24:44.049 align:middle line:90%
We've got to think differently.

00:24:44.049 --> 00:24:47.486 align:middle line:84%
If we attempt to solve those
crises through the old ways

00:24:47.486 --> 00:24:49.388 align:middle line:84%
of thinking that
led to the crises,

00:24:49.388 --> 00:24:50.856 align:middle line:84%
we know where that's
going to lead.

00:24:50.856 --> 00:24:52.958 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it's happening
with disease and the increase

00:24:52.958 --> 00:24:53.425 align:middle line:90%
in disease.

00:24:53.425 --> 00:24:53.792 align:middle line:90%
It's happening--

00:24:53.792 --> 00:24:54.393 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: When we think
about our bodies, sure.

00:24:54.393 --> 00:24:55.861 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --with the
economic system.

00:24:55.861 --> 00:24:57.363 align:middle line:84%
It's happening
everywhere around us.

00:24:57.363 --> 00:24:58.197 align:middle line:90%
It's happening everywhere.

00:24:58.197 --> 00:25:00.199 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: This idea of
survival of the strongest

00:25:00.199 --> 00:25:02.434 align:middle line:84%
and that competition,
violent competition, is good,

00:25:02.434 --> 00:25:05.371 align:middle line:84%
it's so deeply entrenched
into our psyche,

00:25:05.371 --> 00:25:08.006 align:middle line:84%
consciously and in many
cases unconsciously,

00:25:08.006 --> 00:25:11.143 align:middle line:84%
and it has been since 1859,
since Darwin introduced this.

00:25:11.143 --> 00:25:13.045 align:middle line:84%
Now, it's about to take
on a new dimension.

00:25:13.045 --> 00:25:13.879 align:middle line:90%
Can I go to the next level?

00:25:13.879 --> 00:25:14.747 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's why you're here.

